Within the study area, I-64 connects to numerous businesses, homes, schools, and recreational

Within the study area, I-64 is predominantly two lanes in each direction, with auxiliary lanes (acceleration
and deceleration lanes) at the interchanges listed below. Variations in this two lane configuration occur at
four locations. At Bowers Hill, I-64 West begins as a three lane section, with two lanes generated from I-
664 and one lane generated from I-264. This third lane is dropped on the left, east of the bridge over
Rotunda Avenue. The second location where there is a variation in the two lane alignment is on I-64
West, east of the Great Bridge Boulevard partial interchange. At this location, two lanes are added on the
right side as a Collector-Distributor (C-D) Road approaching the I-464 interchange. The third location
where there are more than two lanes in each direction occurs on I-64 East under the I-464 bridge. At this
location, I-64 East functions as a three-lane facility. Prior to reaching the High Rise Bridge, this third
lane is dropped on the left side. The fourth location where I-64 deviates from its two-lane configuration
occurs prior to the interchange at Bowers Hill on I-64 East. At this location, a third lane is added on the
right which exits onto I-264 and the two left lanes exit onto I-664.
The mainline typical section (excluding the High Rise Bridge) includes 12-foot travel lanes, a 10-foot
paved outside shoulder and a 3-foot paved median or left shoulder. The posted speed limit is 60 miles per
The following interchanges are located within the study area:
Exit 297 – Military Highway (Route 13) – Diamond interchange with all ramp terminals
offset from one another along Route 13;
Exit 296 – George Washington Highway (Route 17) – Modified cloverleaf interchange with
loop ramps in the northwest, northeast and southwest quadrants only;
Exit 292 - Great Bridge Boulevard (VA Route 190) – Partial Diamond interchange with only
one exit ramp from I-64 West onto Great Bridge Boulevard; and
Exit 290 – I-464 – Cloverleaf interchange with a C-D roadway along I-64 West.
A key component of the I-64 corridor within the study area is the High Rise Bridge. Originally
constructed in 1969, the High Rise Bridge is a four lane double-leaf bascule span bridge with a 65-foot
unopened vertical clearance. The bridge carries a mile long portion of the I-64 corridor across the
Southern Branch of the Elizabeth River at mile marker 7.1 of the Atlantic Intracoastal Waterway (AICW).
Owned and operated by VDOT, the bridge opens upon vessel demand approximately 25 times per year.
The bridge includes four, 12-foot wide travel lanes with three-foot wide right and left shoulders.

Traffic data utilized includes a combination of short-term count data and continuous count station data
collected in 2012 and 2013. However, due to the Gilmerton Bridge replacement project, which resulted
in permanent single lane closures and regular nighttime road closures along Route 13 during the traffic
data collection period, 2008 count data along Route 13 (prior to the beginning of lane closures and

Balanced average weekday daily traffic (AWDT) and AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes were
developed to document existing conditions. Raw traffic volumes were reviewed throughout the study
area to determine the peak hour at each count location. Common AM and PM peak hours were identified
as 6:45 to 7:45 AM and 4:30 to 5:30 PM, respectively, based on a review of peak hour volumes along I-
64 and major facilities serving I-64 (i.e., I-464, I-664, and I-264).
Due to the nighttime closures of the Gilmerton Bridge, nighttime traffic volumes throughout the study
area were impacted by the diversion of traffic from Route 13 to the signed detour routes. To adjust the
AWDT at count locations impacted by the detour route, nighttime traffic volumes for count locations
unaffected by the detours were reviewed and the portion of daily traffic volume occurring during the
nighttime hours between 8:00 PM and 5:00 AM was calculated. Based on a review of the count locations
not impacted by the detour, the nighttime traffic volume between 8:00 PM and 5:00 AM averaged 12
percent of the daily traffic volume. The 12 percent nighttime factor was then applied to count locations
impacted by the detours to adjust the nighttime traffic counts to expected non-detour traffic volumes. It
should be noted that this methodology did not impact the peak hour traffic volumes and resulted in minor
adjustments to the AWDTs given the relatively small portion of traffic that occurs during the nighttime

page.text: Transportation System Management/Transportation Demand Management (TSM/TDM) strategies would
involve minor improvements to the I-64 corridor. TSM typically consists of strategies that improve
traffic flow, improve signalization, convert existing general purpose (GP) lanes to managed lanes,
improve intersections, and implement information programs. TDM typically consist of strategies that
encourage new driving habits through staggered commuting hours, telecommuting, car and vanpooling,
ridesharing and the utilization of park and ride facilities. As detailed in the Alternatives Development
Technical Report (VDOT, 2014), possible TSM/TDM opportunities for the I-64 corridor could include:
Encourage commuters to carpool/vanpool to work;
Expand park and ride lots, using educational campaigns to promote carpooling to work, and
work with major regional employers to promote staggered work hours and/or telecommuting;
Encourage transit as an alternative mode, by enhancing existing transit options within the
Preserve and improve pedestrian/bicyclist accommodations for roads crossing over or under
Optimize traffic signal timing along signalized arterials in the study area and pursuing
strategies to better coordinate traffic signals such as adaptive signal control.
The TSM/TDM Alternative does not include capacity improvements and involves only minor work to the
existing I-64 corridor. Therefore, because this alternative does not meet the Purpose and Need of the
study by not addressing the capacity, safety, or evacuation needs of the corridor, it was not retained as an
individual, stand-alone alternative. The retained Build Alternatives do not preclude TSM/TDM elements
should they be considered in the future.

Using the screenline refinement procedures described in NCHRP 255 Report: Highway Traffic for
Urbanized Area Project Planning and Design (TRB, 1982) future year 2034 AWDT volumes were
adjusted. The final 2034 adjusted AWDT volumes were derived using the VDOT-reviewed NCHRP 255
post-processor spreadsheet. The purpose of these computations is to adjust the future year link
assignments and to take into account various assignment errors in the base model. The underlying
assumption is that errors that occur in the base year assignment will continue to occur proportionally in
any future year forecasts. The ratio adjustment is based on the ratio of the actual base year traffic count
and the base year traffic assignment, multiplied by the future year traffic forecast. The difference
adjustment is the difference between the actual base year traffic count and the base year traffic
assignment, added to the future year traffic forecast. An average of the ratio and difference adjustment
methods were applied and the volumes were further refined according to base year and future year
capacities. After the final 2034 adjusted AWDT volumes were determined, a yearly linear growth rate of
1.2 percent derived from a trend line between historic counts and 2013 traffic counts was applied to
obtain future year (2040) AWDT volumes. A secondary check was completed to ensure that all volumes
balanced after the yearly linear growth rate was applied. In cases where the rounding caused a volume
imbalance along the corridor, minor volume adjustments were applied to the future year (2040) AWDTs.

AM and PM peak hour traffic forecasts were calculated based on the post-processed AWDT volumes and

of a K-factor is critical to the calculation of peak hour traffic volumes (or design hourly volumes, DHV).

AASHTO’s Green Book provides guidance regarding the selection of a DHV for highway design
purposes. Although the 30th highest hour is suggested for rural highways, AASHTO states that in urban
Interstate 64 / High Rise Bridge Corridor Study
areas, an appropriate DHV may be determined based on typical peak hour volumes. AASHTO also states
that there is typically little difference between the 30th and the 200th highest hourly volume. Based on a
comparison of the calculated K-factors for the 30th, 50th, and 100th highest hours and the K-factors based
on the balanced existing peak hour volumes, the K-factor corresponding to 100th highest hour (by
direction) was selected for use in generating design hourly volumes (i.e., 8.99 percent along I-64 East and
9.13 percent along I-64 West). These values reflect a typical peak hour volume along the corridor and
provide a consistent approach to the generation of design hourly volumes along I-64 within the study
area. For other roadways within the study area, including ramps, K-factors calculated based on the
existing 2013 peak hour volumes and AWDTs were utilized.
